After the liberal international order
Cambridge—Many analysts believe that the liberal international order ended with China's rise and the election of Donald Trump as U.S. president.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he strive to revive it?
Perhaps the outcome wasn't that, but he must find some alternative.
Critics point out that the U.S. order since 1945 was neither global nor always very liberal, and this is correct.
It excludes more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and includes many authoritarian states.
US hegemony is always exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful country must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided — and Americans will also suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic goal of the Biden administration should be to establish an institution-based international system, with different member states participating in handling different matters.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
During the 1990s and 21st century, both countries have been unable to balance American power, while the United States has pursued the pursuit of freedom values above the sovereignty of states.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without ever obtaining approval from the UN Security Council.
It also supported a "Responsibility to Protect" resolution passed by the UN General Assembly in 2005, aimed at protecting citizens who were subjected to cruel treatment by their own governments — — and the United States later used this principle in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect citizens in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as American arrogance in the post-Cold War era — — for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya eventually led to regime change, Russia and China felt deceived — — while defenders of the action describe it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
No matter what, the growth of China and Russia's power more strictly limits the freedom of interventionist actions.
Then what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty as stipulated in the UN Charter, which states that a country can only wage war for self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the situation of occupying neighboring countries' territories by force has been very rare, and once it occurs, it incurs high costs in the form of sanctions (such as Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
Additionally, the Security Council often authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled countries, and political cooperation has also successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This rule-based order dimension remains critically important.
In terms of economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will be the decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is threatened.
Although China complains that the U.S. is blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. position is consistent with sovereignty requirements.
After all, China has blocked the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter in China for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
At the same time, despite the outbreak of this current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
In contrast, interdependence in the ecological field has created insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, because the threats are transnational.
Regardless of the setbacks to economic globalization, environmental globalization will continue, because it is subject to biological and physical laws, which are unaffected by contemporary geopolitical logic.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no country is capable of solving them independently.
On issues such as the 2019新冠疫情 and climate change, power also has what is called a positive-sum dimension.
Under such premises, merely thinking about exercising power over others is insufficient.
We must also think from the dimension of exercising power in cooperation with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are beneficial to us and to others.
Since Nixon met with Mao in 1972, despite ideological differences, this has not affected cooperation between China and the United States.
The challenge Biden faces is whether China and the United States can cooperate to produce global public goods while competing in traditional great power rivalry areas.
The cyberspace is a new and important issue — — because it is partly transnational but also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Freedom of speech and privacy rules for the internet can be established within democratic countries, but these rules would not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As suggested by the Global Cyber Stability Committee, if authoritarians also want to achieve connectivity, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the fundamental structure of the Internet are also in their interest.
But when they use proxies to conduct information warfare or interfere in elections (which infringes upon sovereignty), it is necessary to strengthen norms through rules such as those negotiated during the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union to limit escalation in maritime incidents (although ideological hostility still exists).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Advocating for free values in cyberspace does not mean the United States is unilaterally disarming.
Instead, the United States should differentiate between permissible public persuasion through soft power and hard power such as secret information warfare, and it must certainly retaliate when the other side launches secret information warfare.
It would allow Russia and China to openly broadcast programs and radio broadcasts, but secret coordinated actions such as manipulating social media are not permitted.
Moreover, the United States will continue to criticize these countries' human rights records.
Polls show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, yet does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values these values.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue is whether the United States can work with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while simultaneously collaborating with a broader range of countries to manage rule-based international institutions needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
